ce:section.ce:para:
Fluorescent CDs with properties like excellent water solubility and quantum yield of 16.87 % were synthesized by adopting a reported hydrothermal route [33]. The formation of CDs was established by FT-IR, atomic force microscopy (AFM), high-resolution transmission electron microscopy (HRTEM) and field emission scanning electron microscopy (FESEM) (Fig. 1
                        ). Surface functional groups of CDs were characterized by FT-IR (Fig. 1a), which shows peaks at 3234 cm−1 and 1639 cm−1 that correspond to the stretching vibrations of OH and sp2 CC bonds, respectively. A peak at around 1710 cm−1, appeared as a shoulder peak of stronger sp2 CC stretching peak, describes CO of carboxylate group on the surface of CDs, which is responsible for a negative surface charge of −24.41 mV, as revealed by zeta potential measurement (Fig. S1a). UV–Vis and fluorescence spectra were obtained to understand the optical properties of CDs. In UV–Vis spectra, a shoulder at 245 nm and a strong absorption band at 310 nm correspond to π–π* transition of CC and n–π* transition of CO, respectively and the fluorescence spectra recorded at different excitation wavelengths ranging from 300 nm to 540 nm confirm the excitation dependent emission property of the CDs (Fig. S2) [33]. Further, the morphology of CDs was visualized by AFM, HRTEM and FESEM demonstrating the uniform size (average particle size of 5 nm, Fig. S3a, SI) and spherical shape of CDs with excellent dispersibility (Fig. 1). Further, the thin MnO2 sheets were prepared by the reduction of KMnO4 with MES buffer [33]. UV–vis spectroscopy, AFM analysis, followed by DLS affirmed that MnO2 sheets were free from KMnO4 contamination. AFM revealed the average thickness MnO2 nanosheets as 4−6 nm (Fig. 2
                        ), and the average size of 211 nm was suggested by DLS (Fig. S3b).
